{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"808b97a2a9ad1b3ea0b66262ec6309e875cb9c566e6e1910cb41b139f5289126","slug":"pages.m15-hypothesis-testing-for-the-population-proporti-11","location":"/pages/213-m15-hypothesis-testing-for-the-population-proportion-p-12.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Hypothesis Testing for the Population Proportion p (12 of 13)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"thumbnail":"/build/image299-5038596a4ebec161815a7a6951c04bbd.gif","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"213-m15-hypothesis-testing-for-the-population-proportion-p-12.md","url":"/build/213-m15-hypothesis-t-1ee2766143b1a9eedad8488806883d3d.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"Q1uRuaFRrt"}],"key":"Ahjqim8mfZ"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Apply the concepts of: sample size, statistical significance vs. practical importance, and the relationship between hypothesis testing and confidence intervals.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"qWL6wd2lyb"}],"key":"hpplEqhdiE"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"4. Hypothesis Testing and Confidence Intervals","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"apToIFZSXG"}],"identifier":"id-4-hypothesis-testing-and-confidence-intervals","label":"4. Hypothesis Testing and Confidence Intervals","html_id":"id-4-hypothesis-testing-and-confidence-intervals","implicit":true,"key":"XL69UtA4O9"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The last topic we want to discuss is the relationship between hypothesis testing and confidence intervals. Even though the flavor of these two forms of inference is different (confidence intervals estimate a parameter, and hypothesis testing assesses the evidence in the data against one claim and in favor of another), there is a strong link between them.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"DVGMbroXLR"}],"key":"y9b21C8NGZ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We will explain this link (using the z-test and confidence interval for the population proportion), and then explain how confidence intervals can be used after a test has been carried out.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"JD7b2uyoKS"}],"key":"Qy96wRN6ql"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Recall that a confidence interval gives us a set of plausible values for the unknown population parameter. We may therefore examine a confidence interval to informally decide if a proposed value of population proportion seems plausible.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"CEw3KLqnb3"}],"key":"DVagLCZaKB"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For example, if a 95% confidence interval for p, the proportion of all U.S. adults already familiar with Viagra in May 1998, was (.61, .67), then it seems clear that we should be able to reject a claim that only 50% of all U.S. adults were familiar with the drug, since based on the confidence interval, .50 is not one of the plausible values for p.","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"aIlGrjhRq2"}],"key":"F9PaM1Em9J"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In fact, the information provided by a confidence interval can be formally related to the information provided by a hypothesis test. (","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"NTotwUVDdv"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Comment:","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"dsYpmdye7A"}],"key":"rAYRDpZrxy"},{"type":"text","value":" The relationship is more straightforward for two-sided alternatives, and so we will not present results for the one-sided cases.)","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"yrysoFv2v3"}],"key":"VmKln8YOqk"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Suppose we want to carry out the ","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"tsMqJk5IKx"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"two-sided test:","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"Ptt853JMLc"}],"key":"Dys7ziTyFk"}],"key":"NiYD654Ea0"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/image299-5038596a4ebec161815a7a6951c04bbd.gif","alt":"H_0: p = p_0 and H_a: p ≠ p_0","key":"IM6iYOEZBA","urlSource":"images/image299.gif"},{"type":"caption","c